TY  - JOUR
T1  - On Statistical Discrimination as a Failure of Social Learning: A Multiarmed Bandit Approach
AU  - Komiyama, Junpei
AU  - Noda, Shunya
Y1  - 2024/03/29
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2026/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2022.00893
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2022.00893
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 442
EP  - 455
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We analyze statistical discrimination in hiring markets using a multiarmed bandit model. Myopic firms face workers arriving with heterogeneous observable characteristics. The association between the worker?s skill and characteristics is unknown ex ante; thus, firms need to learn it. Laissez-faire causes perpetual underestimation: minority workers are rarely hired, and therefore, the underestimation tends to persist. Even a marginal imbalance in the population ratio frequently results in perpetual underestimation. We demonstrate that a subsidy rule that is implemented as temporary affirmative action effectively alleviates discrimination stemming from insufficient data.This paper was accepted by Nicolas Stier-Moses, Special Issue on the Human-Algorithm Connection.Funding: This work was supported by the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada [Grant 430-2020-00088] and JST ERATO [Grant JPMJER2301], Japan.Supplemental Material: The online appendix and data files are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.00893.
